01:00:17.890 --> 01:00:18.890
as well.

01:00:18.890 --> 01:00:20.820
Are we just going to let
economics drive this?

01:00:20.820 --> 01:00:22.570
Is there going to be
some policy involved?

01:00:22.570 --> 01:00:25.730
Is there a smarter way to
do it, not only from a cost

01:00:25.730 --> 01:00:29.090
perspective, but from a societal
perspective or an energy grid

01:00:29.090 --> 01:00:30.750
robustness point of view?

01:00:30.750 --> 01:00:32.330
What are the right choices here?

01:00:32.330 --> 01:00:34.950
There's a lot of open questions
right now in the field.

01:00:34.950 --> 01:00:37.130
And what about energy storage?

01:00:37.130 --> 01:00:40.540
Are we going to store it in
terms of batteries and fuel?

01:00:40.540 --> 01:00:42.080
Centralized storage?

01:00:42.080 --> 01:00:44.740
Are we just going dump it into
the grid and be free riders?

01:00:44.740 --> 01:00:46.360
Let the grid handle it, somehow.

01:00:46.360 --> 01:00:49.190
Hope that the grid a stable
enough that when a lot of solar

01:00:49.190 --> 01:00:51.450
is being produced and when
no solar is being produced,

01:00:51.450 --> 01:00:53.760
it'll just be able
to accommodate.

01:00:53.760 --> 01:00:56.316
I guess the resistance in the
turbines of the fossil fuel

01:00:56.316 --> 01:00:57.940
plants will either
increase or decrease

01:00:57.940 --> 01:01:00.619
depending on how much energy
we're pumping into the grid.

01:01:00.619 --> 01:01:03.160
And so at the end of the day,
