01:01:43.380 --> 01:01:45.910
So that puts it
all in perspective,

01:01:45.910 --> 01:01:48.590
I'm not going to get
too much into this.

01:01:48.590 --> 01:01:51.820
I'm just going to say one
quick word about CO2, energy,

01:01:51.820 --> 01:01:53.850
and climate change.

01:01:53.850 --> 01:01:56.360
You hear a lot of
talk about, at least

01:01:56.360 --> 01:02:01.330
from the political sector, that
scientists are, shall we say,

01:02:01.330 --> 01:02:04.630
in a lot of debate whether
climate change exists or not.

01:02:04.630 --> 01:02:06.720
That is patently false.

01:02:06.720 --> 01:02:11.799
The majority of
scientists, upwards of 96%,

01:02:11.799 --> 01:02:13.340
believe that there
is strong evidence

01:02:13.340 --> 01:02:17.310
to support the fact that human
energy consumption, especially

01:02:17.310 --> 01:02:19.560
the high CO2 intensity of
our energy consumption,

01:02:19.560 --> 01:02:21.896
is driving some form
of climate change.

01:02:21.896 --> 01:02:24.270
What the magnitude is and what
the impact is-- obviously,

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:26.070
that is still under discussion.

01:02:26.070 --> 01:02:28.580
But the reality
that our emission

01:02:28.580 --> 01:02:31.180
of energy-- our emission of
CO2 as a result of energy

01:02:31.180 --> 01:02:34.140
use, our fossil fuel energy use,
is driving some form of climate

01:02:34.140 --> 01:02:37.850
change that there is widespread
consensus among the established

01:02:37.850 --> 01:02:39.240
scientists in the field.

01:02:39.240 --> 01:02:41.740
Now if you want to do some back
of the envelope calculations

01:02:41.740 --> 01:02:45.040
just to convince yourself
that we, tiny, puny, little

01:02:45.040 --> 01:02:47.690
human beings are having
an impact on our world,

01:02:47.690 --> 01:02:48.930
do this for me.

01:02:48.930 --> 01:02:51.810
Take the total energy
consumption rate.

01:02:51.810 --> 01:02:53.270
This is the energy burn rate.

01:02:53.270 --> 01:02:56.550
So it's the average
power-- average

01:02:56.550 --> 01:02:58.760
rate of electricity use.

01:02:58.760 --> 01:03:05.800
Look at just the fossil
fuel based energy sources.

01:03:05.800 --> 01:03:09.640
Or if you prefer, take
the average CO2 intensity

01:03:09.640 --> 01:03:14.770
of our energy mix, which
somewhere around 600 or maybe

01:03:14.770 --> 01:03:17.680
800 grams of CO2
per kilowatt hour.

01:03:17.680 --> 01:03:22.120
And then look at that
amount of CO2 emitted.

01:03:22.120 --> 01:03:25.610
You can calculate how much
CO2 is emitted per unit time

01:03:25.610 --> 01:03:28.280
from our energy mix knowing the
carbon intensity of our energy

01:03:28.280 --> 01:03:29.240
mix.

01:03:29.240 --> 01:03:31.370
Then do a quick back of
the envelope calculation.

01:03:31.370 --> 01:03:34.170
Assume that our atmosphere
is 30 kilometers thick.

01:03:34.170 --> 01:03:36.652
It's a generous assumption.

01:03:36.652 --> 01:03:38.860
The density of the atmosphere
dwindles pretty quickly

01:03:38.860 --> 01:03:39.800
above 10 kilometers.

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:41.750
But assume it's 30
kilometers thick.

01:03:41.750 --> 01:03:44.070
And then dissolve
all of that carbon

01:03:44.070 --> 01:03:46.070
that we're creating
from this energy mix

01:03:46.070 --> 01:03:48.565
into that thin shell
surrounding our earth.

01:03:48.565 --> 01:03:52.660
Our earth is on the order of
6,370 kilometers in radius.

01:03:52.660 --> 01:03:55.884
And it's only 30 kilometers
thick, the atmosphere.

01:03:55.884 --> 01:03:58.300
That's why those beautiful
photos from the space missions,

01:03:58.300 --> 01:04:01.110
when you see that thin
blue shell on the planet,

01:04:01.110 --> 01:04:02.880
right-- that's the atmosphere.

01:04:02.880 --> 01:04:04.460
It's really, really thin.

01:04:04.460 --> 01:04:07.900
Just do a quick carbon
density analysis.

01:04:07.900 --> 01:04:12.100
And you'll see that we're adding
hi tens of parts per million

01:04:12.100 --> 01:04:14.572
of CO2 to the atmosphere.

01:04:14.572 --> 01:04:17.030
And then you look at the total
CO2 in the atmosphere, which

01:04:17.030 --> 01:04:19.240
is in the order of
400 parts per million,

01:04:19.240 --> 01:04:22.940
and you'll see that we're adding
an appreciable amount, just

01:04:22.940 --> 01:04:25.206
given the carbon intensity
of our energy mix

01:04:25.206 --> 01:04:27.330
and the total volume of
atmosphere into which we're

01:04:27.330 --> 01:04:29.270
dumping that carbon.

01:04:29.270 --> 01:04:31.080
And so the question
of whether or not

01:04:31.080 --> 01:04:33.480
we are adding carbon to
the atmosphere, I think,

01:04:33.480 --> 01:04:35.597
is indisputable, based
on some quick back

01:04:35.597 --> 01:04:37.430
of the envelope
calculations and, of course,

01:04:37.430 --> 01:04:39.170
the more in-depth models.

01:04:39.170 --> 01:04:42.390
The only place where you can
have some wiggle room to argue

01:04:42.390 --> 01:04:45.600
is whether or not CO2 actually
influences the climate.

01:04:45.600 --> 01:04:47.540
And for that, there
are a number of studies

01:04:47.540 --> 01:04:49.580
discussing that point.

01:04:49.580 --> 01:04:54.340
I would refer you, specifically,
to these here, published

01:04:54.340 --> 01:04:57.580
in Science in 2005, that
discuss historical correlations

01:04:57.580 --> 01:05:00.660
over the last 600,000
years, correlating CO2

01:05:00.660 --> 01:05:05.110
and mean global temperatures
based on oxygen isotope

01:05:05.110 --> 01:05:08.900
ratios containing gas bubbles,
for example, in ice cores.

01:05:08.900 --> 01:05:11.510
So I would say if you're
arguing whether or not

01:05:11.510 --> 01:05:14.120
we're having an influence
on our atmosphere,

01:05:14.120 --> 01:05:17.560
I would say that is a
difficult position to take.

01:05:17.560 --> 01:05:20.409
The only room that I would
give you some room to maneuver

01:05:20.409 --> 01:05:21.950
would be if you
said, well, you know,

01:05:21.950 --> 01:05:24.440
CO2 really isn't that
bad in the atmosphere,

01:05:24.440 --> 01:05:26.205
despite what our
infrared absorption data

01:05:26.205 --> 01:05:27.580
seems to indicate,
that it really

01:05:27.580 --> 01:05:31.220
does absorb infrared
light and reemit it.

01:05:31.220 --> 01:05:34.800
So that's what I have to
say about the climate, which

01:05:34.800 --> 01:05:37.592
